wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":17,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth de Blackpool was born about 1365, in Blackpool, Devon, England. She married Robert Molton Avenell about 1380, in South Molton, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1388, in Lancashire, England, at the age of 24."},"et":{"about 1365–1388":"umbes 1365–1388","1360–1384":"1360–1384","1384–1460":"1384–1460","1365–1388":"1365–1388","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1388":"1388","1365":"1365","1384":"1384","about 1365":"umbes 1365","1460":"1460","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","about 1384":"umbes 1384","Blackpool, Lancashire, England":"Blackpool, Lancashire, England","Blackpool, Devon, England":"Blackpool, Devon, England","North Molten, Devonshire, England":"North Molton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","South Molton, Devon, England":"South Mo